{{for|other institutions with similar names|Concordia University (disambiguation)}}
'''Concordia College''' is a four-year [[coeducation]]al Lutheran-affiliated [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts college]] located in [[Bronxville, New York|the village of Bronxville]], in [[Westchester County, New York |Westchester County]], [[New York]].  

The college was founded in 1881 and is part of the [[Concordia University System]], operated by the [[Lutheran Church - Missouri Synod]].  While Concordia is an intentionally [[Christian]] college within the Lutheran tradition, it welcomes students of all religious and cultural backgrounds. 

==Accreditation and affiliations==
Concordia holds [[educational accreditation|institutional accreditation]] by the [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]]. The [[Social Work]] program is accredited by the [[Council on Social Work Education]] and the [[teacher education]] program is accredited by the [[National Council for the Accreditation of Teacher Education]] (NCATE). 

The College is registered by the [[New York State Education Department]] and the International Center for [[English as a Second Language]] and is a member of the American Association of Intensive English Programs.

==Athletics==
The Concordia Clippers are members of [[NCAA]] [[Division II]] and compete in the [[East Coast Conference]] in men<U+2019>s baseball, basketball, cross country, soccer, and tennis, women<U+2019>s basketball, cross country, soccer, softball, tennis, and volleyball.

==Notable people==
* [[Arlen Gargagliano]], writer, educator and TV personality, is a former assistant professor of English at the College.<ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/1995/05/21/nyregion/lessons-in-understanding-at-a-hot-stove.html Lessons in Understanding at a Hot Stove] New York Times. Published May 21, 1995. Accessed June 24, 2009.</ref>

